    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Tire Crash Victims</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New York State Trial Lawyers Association Pres Lenore Kramer letter disputes Sept 17 article contending that lawyers who represent victims 'seem happy' in face of tire fiasco</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Road to Truth Paved With Fingerpointing'' (Week in Review, Sept. 17):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Road to Truth Paved With Fingerpointing'' (Week in Review, Sept. 17):</p>
        <p>I take offense at your suggestion that lawyers who represent the victims ''seem happy'' in the face of the tire fiasco, which resulted in the maiming and deaths of innocent victims. This is akin to suggesting that doctors are delighted in the face of train wrecks and plane crashes.</p>
        <p>You say the lawyers ''say little about why they kept almost two dozen fatal crashes out of a federal database of safety problems for years, even as they filed multimillion-dollar lawsuits.'' The responsibility of keeping the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration informed of problems with their products lies with Ford Motor Company and Firestone, not the lawyers representing victims.</p>
        <p>Such large companies impose confidentiality upon litigants and their lawyers even where the product is defectively designed or otherwise dangerous. These companies make confidentiality a requirement for any settlement.</p>
        <p>LENORE KRAMER  President, New York State  Trial Lawyers Association  New York, Sept. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
